observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete and detailed physical inventory of all the LGU’s properties in accordance with the new guidelines and procedures prescribed by COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31 2020, prepare and submit, within the deadlines set, the RPCPPE together with the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System of the LGU;
Instruct the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory Map and Property Cards for each type of properties as basis for reconciliation with the PPE accounts with the accounting records;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain, in relation to the local road networks of the LGU, Local Road Network Ledger Card (LRNLC), including the regular property ledger cards, also as basis for reconciliation with the General Ledger account balances and with the property records;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to update status of completed infrastructure projects and draw a journal entry voucher to transfer completed infrastructure projects to appropriate PPE accounts to present fairly the balances of Construction in Progress and appropriate PPE accounts and consequently recognize the depreciation expenses pertaining thereto;
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare a JEV to reclassify to Seaport System account payment for the land expansion of Mobo port amounting to ₱0.10 million erroneously recorded as Land account and PPE accounts which acquisition cost falls below the capitalization threshold of ₱15,000.00 to Semi-Expendable Property accounts and to recognize as expenses upon issuance of the Semi-Expendable property to the end-user;
Execute a deed of donation to recipient schools of buildings, equipment and other PPE donated by the LGU and to draw a JEV dropping off the respective PPE accounts in the LGU’s books of accounts and transmit it to the respective divisions or autonomous schools together with other documents relative to the buildings and other PPE items to enable their Accountant or Bookkeeper to record it in their books of accounts; and
Require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to initiate the reconciliation of their respective records and avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with a reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that Management require:
The Municipal Accountant to:
Observe the Modified Accrual method of accounting for income from Real Property Taxes in accordance with the MNGAS for LGUs;
Observe due diligence in the recording of transactions by using the appropriate accounts under COA Circular No. 2015-009 and following the series of proforma entries in taking up all transactions on RPT and SET; and
To reconcile the affected accounts and effect the necessary/adjusting correcting entries to present fairly the balances in the Financial Statements;
The Municipal Treasurer to prepare and update the RPTAR/RPT Index Card and the Certified List of Taxpayers and submit the latter to the Accounting Office at the end of the year to be used as basis in establishing the RPT/SET Receivable;
The Municipal Assessor to prepare and update the Assessment Roll for newly assessed or reassessed properties on time and furnish the Municipal Treasurer except only where the Assessor’s records are computerized and readily available to the Municipal Treasurer thru a local area network.

We recommend that the LCE ensure that the Municipal Accountant:
Observe the proper recording of the reciprocal accounts, Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds in order not to increase the unreconciled balances;
Reconcile the reciprocal accounts of all funds maintained by the Municipality, by identifying the causes of discrepancies in the corresponding subsidiary accounts and to effect immediate adjustments in the books of accounts;
Conduct regular reconciliation of the accounts to ensure the accuracy of the reciprocal accounts;
File all necessary documents for proper documentation; and
Exhaust all means to retrieve the necessary data/documents to reconcile the prior year’s discrepancies and make adjustments.

We recommended that Management require:
The Property/Supply Officer to prepare and submit duly accomplished Report on the Physical Count of Inventories;
The Accountant to properly record the purchases of inventories for consumption or distribution in the appropriate inventory accounts and the consumption or distribution thereof as expense, upon receipt of SSMI of a given period;
The Accounting Unit to maintain Supplies Ledger Cards and the Local Treasury Unit or the General Services Office to maintain Stock Cards as required in both their offices; and
Both the Accountant and the Supply Officer to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records and make adjustment, when necessary, to reflect the true balance of the Inventory Accounts in the Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management require:
The BAC Secretariat to consolidate the PPMP included in the budget proposal into an indicative APP and the BAC to make a final recommendation of the appropriate procurement modality of identified PPA in the PPMP to the HoPE and submit regularly the required APP to the Audit Team;
The Supply and Property Division to consolidate his purchase request with other purchase request of similar items and perform activities pertaining to the mode of procurement to be used for the requested supplies and materials before making any purchases;
The concerned official to submit explanation/justification and the lacking supporting documents for the deficiencies noted; and
The Accountant to exercise due diligence in the verification of the propriety and completeness of supporting documents and to faithfully adhere to Section 4 of PD No. 1445 and other related laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended the following:
That the Office of the Municipal Accountant give utmost attention to the preparation and submission of the required bank reconciliation statements for the bank accounts under the General Fund pursuant to Section 474 of Republic Act (RA) No. 7160 and COA Circular No.96-011 dated October 2, 1996 and substantiate the unreconciled difference thereof substantially amounting to ₱6,703,258.75;
That the ICO-Municipal Treasurer prepare and maintain updated cash books and reconcile the same with the Accounting records;
Any error and reconciling item discovered in the reconciliation process must accordingly be adjusted in the respective records which need correction/revision, to arrive at a correct and reliable cash in bank balance; and
Consider closing bank account/s which is/are deemed unnecessary or a duplication of an existing account.

We recommended that Management:
Institute measures to monitor its cash balances and implement additional revenue collection strategies and austerity measures to increase collection and improve its cash position;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to review and reconcile the composition of payables to determine the validity of claims and accuracy of the amounts;
Give priority to pay all outstanding trust liabilities to BIR, GSIS, Pag-Ibig, and Philhealth to avoid the incurrence of penalties and surcharges;
Ensure that all disbursements would pass through the Budget Office for recording in the registry, as appropriate; and
Ensure the funds received are to be used solely for the intended purpose.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to strictly apply the perpetual inventory method in the recording of supplies and materials to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials and prepare and maintain updated Stock Ledger Cards and Stock Cards for all the supplies and materials procured by the LGU;
Require the Requisitioning Office to prepare RIS when requesting for Supplies and Materials;
Require the GSO to desist from issuing Supplies and Materials without the RIS, and consolidate the RIS monthly in the SSMI and regularly submit the same to the Accountant in order for the latter to prepare a JEV to recognize the issuance and use the same as basis to record the corresponding expense; and
Require the conduct of complete annual physical count of Inventory in accordance with Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Vol.1.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete and detailed physical inventory of all the LGU’s properties in accordance with the new guidelines and procedures prescribed by COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31 2020, prepare and submit, within the deadlines set, the RPCPPE together with the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System of the LGU;
Instruct the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain the Local Road Inventory Map and Property Cards for each type of properties as basis for reconciliation with the PPE accounts with the accounting records;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain, in relation to the local road networks of the LGU, Local Road Network Ledger Card (LRNLC), including the regular property ledger cards, also as basis for reconciliation with the General Ledger account balances and with the property records;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to update status of completed infrastructure projects and draw a journal entry voucher and record the transfer of the completed infrastructure projects, complete with the required documentations to present fairly the balances of Construction in Progress and appropriate PPE accounts and consequently recognize the depreciation expenses pertaining thereto;
Require the Municipal Accountant to reclassify to the proper Inventory account semi-expendable items with estimated useful life of more than one year but less than the capitalization threshold and recorded as PPE. These items must be recorded as expense upon their issuance and tender of corresponding Inventory Custodian Slip to the end-user for proper monitoring, control and accountability;
Execute a deed of donation to recipient schools of buildings, equipment and other PPE donated by the LGU and to draw a JEV dropping off the respective PPE accounts in the LGU’s books of accounts and transmit it to the respective divisions or autonomous schools together with other documents relative to the buildings and other PPE items to enable their Accountant or Bookkeeper to record it in their books of accounts; and
Require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to initiate the reconciliation of their respective records and avail the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, strictly in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 and adjust the books accordingly, in order to come up with a reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that Management:
Create a special trust fund account for the unexpended prior years’ DRRM funds and draw a check from the General Fund to transfer the unexpended amount to the trust fund to ensure funds will not be utilized for purposes other than DRRM purposes;
Observe judicious management of DRRM funds, to include planning, budgeting, and optimal utilization, that is geared towards being disaster-prepared and resilient and be in line with the government’s effort to curtail/eliminate/mitigate the spread of COVID-19 in the community;
Require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Budget and MDRRMO to conduct annual reconciliation of their respective records on the utilization of LDRRMF to avoid inconsistent balances on their reports and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted thereon accordingly; and
Pursue the implementation of unimplemented projects, otherwise, reassess the necessity of re-programming it to other projects or purposes which will be more effective in strengthening capacities of the LGU and its community.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant, the BAC and other officials concerned to submit immediately the DVs and Liquidation Reports with corresponding supporting documents of payments amounting to ₱9.25 million and the lacking required documents for the DVs already submitted;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct thorough review and ensure completeness of supporting documents before effecting any payments in compliance with the applicable rules and regulations;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to record the purchase of welfare goods for distribution, drugs, medicines and supplies in the inventory held for distribution account and not as an outright expense. An inventory control account must be maintained in the General Ledger on a current basis. Issuance must be recorded as they take place in the appropriate expense account based on the SSMI and the ICS or PAR, as applicable in the issuance of equipment; and
Require the BAC to comply with the posting requirements of GPPB Circular No. 2020-001 for information purposes and transparency.

We recommended and reiterated that Management:
Once again, convene the Inventory Committee, conduct the annual physical count of all its property, plant and equipment and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment to the Office of the Auditor;
Require the General Services Officer, in the performance of his mandated functions, to give preferential attention in maintaining an updated Property Cards per category on all property, plant, and equipment as recorded in the list of Property, Plant, and Equipment of accounting records, and thereafter as the transaction occurs. He must also facilitate the proper conduct of the physical count and preparation of the Report in the prescribed form;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain property ledger cards consistent with their accounting records;
Require both offices to reconcile property records ensuring that the balances shown in the prepared RPCPPE agreed with the supply and property records and the book balances in the accounting records, and vice versa; and
For any resulting difference, the Accounting and the General Services Office must work out on tracing the reconciling items, establish their existence/non-existence and determine from there any further action that may be undertaken.

We recommended that Management exhaust all possible means to require the liquidation or settlement of cash advances including, but not limited to, the following:
Demand immediate settlement/liquidation of the outstanding cash advances of all concerned accountable officers pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002;
Require the Municipal Accountant to monitor the grant and liquidation of cash advances and avoid granting additional cash advances unless the previous cash advance is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made;
For long outstanding cash advances, exert effort to retrieve the documents relative thereto, as basis for the issuance of demand letter by the Municipal Accountant; and
Institute appropriate criminal or administrative sanctions for the continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, if warranted.

We recommended and reiterated that Management:
Convene the Inventory Committee, conduct the annual physical count of all its PPE and submit the RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;
Designate or appoint a GSO who will solely handle the said office and perform its mandated functions. Require the GSO to give preferential attention to maintaining an updated Property Cards per category on all PPE as recorded in the list of PPE of accounting records, and thereafter as the transaction occurs. He must also facilitate the proper conduct of the physical count and preparation of the Report in the prescribed form;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain property ledger cards consistent with their accounting records;
Require both the Accounting Office and General Services Office to reconcile property records ensuring that the balances shown in the prepared RPCPPE agreed with the supply and property records and the book balances in the accounting records, and vice versa; and
For any resulting difference, both offices must work out on tracing the reconciling items, establish their existence/non-existence and determine from there any further action that may be undertaken.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to properly account all the land properties of the Municipality by gathering relevant supporting documents from the Municipal Assessor’s Office and effect the necessary adjustments in the books to arrive at a more reliable Land account balance in the Financial Statements in accordance with IPSAS 17 and other applicable accounting standards;
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Assessor to reconcile real property records and ensure that the parcels of land shown in the schedule of land account of FS agreed with the assessor’s office records of tax declaration of lots in the name of the Municipality of Mobo, and vice versa. For any resulting difference, they must work out on tracing the reconciling items, establish their existence/non-existence and determine from there any further action that may be undertaken;
Revisit the documentation over the area/s to which the Municipal structures/improvements were being constructed/introduced and initiate the determination or assignment of costs to land acquired through a non-exchange transaction;
Allocate adequate budget for the titling of the subject land properties in the name of the Municipal Government to establish absolute ownership and reduce the risk of third party claims;
Make a representation with the Land Registration Authority or Register of Deeds to confirm the ownership of all land properties covered by the Tax Declarations on hand and thereafter, secure copies of the Torrens Title or any equivalent document relative thereto; and
No further disbursements must be incurred by the Municipality for any introduction of improvement/construction to private lands unless it is clothed with Usufruct Agreement/Acts of Deeds duly notarized and registered in the name of the Municipality before the Register of Deeds. Otherwise, its corresponding disbursements may not be allowed in audit.

Expedite the completion/updating of the 10-Year Municipal SWM Plan for approval by the NSWMC to serve as guide for the efficient management of solid waste generated within the Municipality’s jurisdiction;
Encourage and provide needed assistance to the remaining 25 barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes; and
Provide the necessary training for SWM collectors and other personnel directly dealing with collection of solid waste to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Development Council to judiciously plan the PPAs to be funded out of the 20 percent EDF in accordance with the existing rules and regulations;
Speed up the implementation of priority development projects  and programs as embodied in the AIP to attain the socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes for the constituents' benefits;
Require the Municipal Budget Office and Municipal Accounting Office to reconcile the ending balance for amortization of loans, establish their existence/non-existence and determine from there any further action that may be undertaken; and
Also, make representation to the Sangguniang Bayan to revert to surplus the unutilized and the unobligated balances/savings of prior year’s projects and use the amount for other Local Government Unit projects that need immediate attention.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Planning Officer and the Budget Officer ensure that proposed PPAs chargeable against the Fund are properly identified/itemized and the related information such as specific timetable and expected output are defined in the AIP to facilitate monitoring and evaluation;
The Municipal Planning and Development Officer abide strictly with the guidelines in the formulation of the 20 percent Development Plan based on equitable allocation of funds pursuant to Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 of the DILG and DBM;
Implement immediately and on timely basis the identified projects under the 20 percent DF;
The members of the BAC schedule early all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave way for their timely implementation and completion; and
Refrain from utilizing the developmental fund for non-allowable programs/projects. The utilized amounts for non-allowable projects must be restituted to the fund in order not to deprive the stakeholders of the benefits they may derive from developmental projects in terms of socio-economic development and environmental management.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
a. Require the General Services Officer, Accounting and General Services Officer, in performance of his mandated functions, to give preferential attention in maintaining an updated Property Cards per category or all property, plant, and equipment as recorded in the list of Property, Plant, and Equipment of accounting records, and thereafter as the transaction occurs. He should also facilitate the proper conduct of the physical count and preparation of the Report in the prescribed form;
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain property ledger cards consistent with their accounting records;
c. Require both offices to reconcile property records ensuring that the balances shown in the prepared RPCPPE agreed with the supply and property records and the book balances in the accounting records, and vice versa;
d. For any resulting difference, the Accounting and the General Services Office should work out on tracing the reconciling items, establish its existence/non-existence and determine from there any further action that may be undertaken; and,
e. Maintain and renew all Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment every three years for the signature of the holder of each item listed in the prepared RPCPPE or based on the old Memorandum Receipts on file.

